<A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 1748<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/1/02 11:46:00 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=143.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   How many megatons would it take to move the Earth?</span><hr size=1> Archimedes once said that if he had a long enough lever he could move the Earth. How large a Hydrogen bomb would be needed to move the Earth? Is it possible? Is there enough available Uranium to do the job? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=stilgar>Stilgar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 20<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/9/02 11:04:00 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=143.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: How many megatons would it take to move the Earth?</span><hr size=1> The mass of the earth is about<br>
6.0 x 10^24 kg<br>
How far do you want to move it?  Say we wanted to increase/decrease its velocity by 1 m/s.<br>
<br>
e=1/2MV^2<br>
<br>
M is constant(we assume) and V is just 1.<br>
so we need to give the earth 3.0x10^24 J of energy.<br>
according to this site:<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.matter-antimatter.com/energy.htm">www.matter-antimatter.com/energy.htm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
A 1 Megaton weapon discharges 4.18 x 10^15 Joules of energy. So we would need a bomb of magnitude 7.17 X10^8 Megatons, or 717000000 Megatons.  about 717 Terratons (mega, giga, terra).  In reality, due to the fact that not ALL the energy will go into moving the earth (some of the energy will be absorbed elastically, some willl just dissipate into space) you'd probably need about a Petaton: a thousand million megatons.<br>
<br>
Other people know better than I about nuclear weapons and could actually say whether it is feasible to generate a shaped nuclear charge of this magnitude. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=stilgar>Stilgar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 27<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/9/02 9:47:04 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=143.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: How many megatons would it take to move the Earth?</span><hr size=1> One of the engineers here said that the best momentum transfer is achieved by detonating approximately .4 Radii from the surface of the target.  so you'd explode the nuke (no shaped nukes apparently) about 1600 miles out in space, and you'd need several Terratons. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 703<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/10/02 9:10:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=143.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: How many megatons would it take to move the Earth?</span><hr size=1> Would that fall into the planet busting class rather than the planet moving?  What effect would several smaller bombs have?  Detonate one every few seconds over a period of time? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=stilgar>Stilgar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 32<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/11/02 3:04:33 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=143.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: How many megatons would it take to move the Earth?</span><hr size=1> basically, the nuke would be designed for maximum momentum transfer.  That is, it would blast as much of the mass of the body off into space (action-reaction, remember) as possible.  Who knows what effect it might have on the earth.  Thats a pretty impressive materials / dynamics problem (molten core, solid crust, shock absorbtion, etc.).  I think it would be fair to say, however, that the fit would hit the shan. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 1779<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/12/02 2:38:19 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=143.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: How many megatons would it take to move the Earth?</span><hr size=1> Several thousand million megatons. I think it's safe to say there isn't enough readily extractable Uranium on Earth to build such a device. The centre of the Earth was recently conjectured to be a 5km diameter sphere of Uranium. That might be enough. Too hot to be mined though. I think.<br>
It's difficult to say if Uranium is abundant enough in the solar system to make such a blast possible. There could be enough to send the Earth spiralling into the Sun or on it's way to Proxima Centaurii. There might barely be enough to move the Earth a millimetre. It might hardly exist at all out there. We need to get out there and take a look. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 712<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/12/02 6:26:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=143.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: How many megatons would it take to move the Earth?</span><hr size=1> What if there was a moon base and nearby there was a nuclear waste<br>
storage area that accidently exploded and knocked the Earth's <br>
moon on an interstellar trajectory?<br>
<br>
Oh wait. It's been done.  It was called Space: 1999<br>
<br>
Did that happen three years ago?  Where was I?<br>
